snippet.description:
Police in Kenya's capital Nairobi have fired tear gas at protesters angered by the death of a 31-year-old blogger in police custody. 
President William Ruto earlier said the man died “at the hands of the police”, contradicting initial accounts of his death. 
Officials had claimed he died due to self-inflicted injuries, but an autopsy revealed that he was assaulted. 
The blogger was known for being critical about political and social issues.

Kenya’s President William Ruto has publicly condemned the death of 31-year-old Albert Ojwang, who died in police custody after being arrested over a social media post accusing a top police officer of corruption. Police initially claimed Ojwang died by hitting his head against a wall, but a government pathologist later said his injuries were unlikely to be self-inflicted. Ruto called the death “heartbreaking and unacceptable” and urged a swift investigation. The case has sparked outrage across Kenya, which is still reeling from last year’s deadly anti-government protests. Five police officers have been suspended, and international voices, including the U.S. and UK, are demanding justice. Rights groups say this reflects a larger pattern of police abuse and silencing of critics.
